{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1784224885,"nonce":"VVYaobJt5r7nF1uRaFBGQyt8niA=","body":"# Quarantine review — sub-project B: review, approve/reject, --force (design)\n\nStatus: design approved 2026-07-16 (Trevor). Sub-project of the quarantine-review\narc; parent design `kref show 4cb93aef7611`, predecessor `kref show 80ed5975ef35`\n(sub-project A). This spec covers ONLY B. A parked flagged writes into the\n`quarantine` namespace; B applies the human decision. C (surfaces) is a separate\nown-cycle sub-project.\n\n## Scope\n\nA leaves a flagged write held in `quarantine` with its payload and an in-context\nreview thread, but nothing is applied to the live target. B is the decision:\n`kref quarantine approve|reject \u003cid\u003e` replays or discards the held write through\nthe normal store write path, resolves the review thread, and records who decided.\nB also redefines `--force` from scan-bypass to inline create+approve, adds\napprove-time stale-replay conflict handling, and closes A's two carry-over\nrefuse-paths (comment edit, resolve-note) so every write surface parks uniformly\ninstead of two still refusing.\n\nDeliverable: after B, a parked item can be approved (applied to the live target,\nor the draft retiered to its destination) or rejected (discarded, content\npreserved, item tombstoned), the review thread is resolved either way, a human at\nthe CLI can `--force` a flagged write through the same audited machinery in one\nstep, and no write surface returns a hard refusal on a flagged body.\n\n## B.1 Commands and dispatch\n\n    kref quarantine approve \u003cid\u003e [-m \u003cnote\u003e]\n    kref quarantine reject  \u003cid\u003e [-m \u003cnote\u003e]\n\nBoth resolve `\u003cid\u003e` through the store (A threaded `searchTierNames` so a\nquarantine id resolves) and dispatch on the item's shape:\n\n- New-entry draft — `kind != quarantine`, carries a `q-dest:\u003ctier\u003e` label. The\n  item body IS the proposed entry. Approve retiers it; reject discards it.\n- Held-op intent-item — `kind == quarantine`, body is the v2 intent JSON.\n  Approve replays the op onto the live target; reject discards the intent.\n\nThe two shapes are the same two A produces; B adds no new item forms.\n\n## B.2 Intent schema v2 — the enrichment A deferred to B\n\nA shipped intent v1 (op payload only). Faithful approval needs two more\npark-time facts, so B revises the intent to v2 and updates the A park primitives\n(`QuarantineUpdate` / `QuarantineComment` / `QuarantineNewEntry`) to capture them.\nNothing v1 has shipped or pushed, so no in-flight migration exists; the schema tag\nmoves 1 -\u003e 2 and a reader rejects an unknown schema with a clear error.\n\n    type intent struct {\n        Schema        int            // 2\n        OpKind        string         // set-body | add-comment | edit-comment | resolve\n        TargetID      string         // the live entry the op applies to\n        Content       string         // new body | comment text | edit body | resolve note\n        Question      bool           // add-comment only\n        ReplyTo       string         // add-comment only\n        CommentTarget string         // edit-comment / resolve: the comment id acted on\n        BaseVersion   int            // versioned-kind CAS base captured at park time\n        Findings      []scan.Finding // rule + line, never the value\n        ActorKind     string         // human | agent\n    }\n\n- `BaseVersion` — the target's version at the moment the write was attempted (the\n  writer's asserted `if_version` when present, else the current head version read\n  during the write). Used for approve-time CAS (B.3).\n- The review-comment id — the question-comment `openReview` opened, so approve and\n  reject resolve the exact thread — is recorded as a `q-review:\u003ccid\u003e` label on the\n  quarantine item, for BOTH shapes (held op and draft). It is a label rather than\n  an intent field because the intent JSON is the item body, marshalled before\n  `openReview` posts the comment, so the cid is not yet known at marshal time. B\n  changes `openReview` to return the created comment id, and both park primitives\n  add the label after posting the review comment.\n\n## B.3 Approve — replay through the normal write path\n\nAn approved write must look exactly like a fresh write, so B replays through the\nexisting store methods (inheriting flock, provenance, DAG merge) rather than\ntouching refs directly.\n\n- New-entry draft: `Retier(id, q-dest tier, approver, actorKind)`. The id and its\n  review thread travel with the entry; it becomes a normal live entry on the\n  destination tier and leaves the queue. The `q-dest` / `q-review` labels are\n  cleared as part of promotion.\n- Held op — dispatch on `OpKind`:\n  - `set-body` -\u003e `Update(target, content, \"\")`\n  - `add-comment` -\u003e `AddComment(target, actorKind, content, question, replyTo)`\n  - `edit-comment` -\u003e `EditComment(target, commentTarget, content)`\n  - `resolve` -\u003e `AddComment(target, actorKind, content, false, commentTarget)`\n    when the note is non-empty, then `ResolveComment(target, commentTarget)`.\n\nStale-replay conflict: before replaying a `set-body` on a versioned kind\n(`todoguard.CheckVersion(kind, BaseVersion, currentVersion)`), approve refuses a\ntarget that advanced since park with a clear conflict (\"target moved vN-\u003evM since\nquarantine; re-review\"), never a clobber. Non-versioned kinds replay as a normal\n`set-body` (DAG merge, identical to a direct `kref update`) — approve imposes no\nstaleness gate a direct write would not have. Append-only ops (`add-comment`,\n`edit-comment`, `resolve`) never conflict.\n\n## B.4 Reject — discard, preserve, tombstone\n\n`reject` never touches the live target. It:\n\n- preserves the proposed content (draft body or intent `Content`) to\n  `$XDG_STATE_HOME/kref/rejected/\u003cid\u003e-\u003cstamp\u003e.md` via the existing\n  `todoguard/recovery.go` helper, so no human work is lost;\n- resolves the review thread as rejected, posting the optional `-m` note;\n- tombstones the item: `Archive(id)` plus a `q-status:rejected` label. The item is\n  preserved for audit (addressable by id), not purged.\n\n## B.5 Post-decision state and audit trail\n\nBoth decisions resolve the review thread (`ResolveComment` on `ReviewComment`,\nafter posting the decider's optional note) and record provenance through the\nnormal ops (the retier / replay / resolve ops are authored by the approving\nactor). Post-decision item state:\n\n- Approved draft: retiered out — it is now a live entry and naturally absent from\n  the queue; no separate tombstone needed.\n- Approved held op: after replay, `Archive(item)` + `q-status:approved` label. The\n  archived item plus the resolved thread are the audit record that a flagged write\n  was reviewed and applied, and by whom.\n- Rejected (either shape): archived + `q-status:rejected` (B.4).\n\nC's `quarantine list` shows only pending items (not archived / not `q-status:*`);\nthe decided items remain reachable by id for audit.\n\n## B.6 --force = inline create + approve\n\n`--force` on the CLI writers is redefined from \"skip the scan\" (today's comment\nbehavior) to \"park then immediately approve\" — create the quarantine item and its\nthread, then run the B.3 approve path in the same command, under the same write\nlock. B adds `--force` to `new` and `update` and changes `comment --force` to the\nnew semantics.\n\nThis is the human's one-step direct-write escape, but unlike scan-bypass it leaves\na full audit trail: an archived `q-status:approved` item, the recorded findings,\nand a resolved thread showing a human force-approved a flagged write. A force on a\nclean (unflagged) body writes directly as today — parking only happens on a\nfinding. MCP exposes no force: an LLM write always parks and awaits a human.\n\n## B.7 Carry-overs closed — uniform gate\n\nA left two write paths still refusing a flagged body instead of parking:\n`comment --edit` and `comment --resolve -m \u003cnote\u003e` (CLI `guardCommentBody`), and\ntheir MCP equivalents (`kref_comment` actions `edit` and `resolve`). B routes all\nfour through the new `edit-comment` / `resolve` intent op-kinds (B.2), so every\none of the write surfaces parks a flagged body. No surface returns a hard refusal\non a flagged write after B; the only refusals left are structural (empty body,\nnot-a-question), never secret-policy.\n\n## Concurrency (\"normal git stuff\")\n\nApprove/reject take the per-repo write lock via the store methods they call. The\nonly real race is two approvals of held ops for the same target: they serialize\nunder the lock and apply in sequence; the second conflicts only if it is a stale\n`set-body` on a versioned kind, surfaced as the B.3 re-review conflict. Distributed\nedits merge on pull as usual. No bespoke concurrency machinery.\n\n## Out of scope (sub-project C)\n\n- `kref quarantine list` / `show` and the `quarantine show` renderer.\n- Read-only MCP `kref_quarantine` (list/show); approve/reject stay human/CLI.\n- Pending count in the cockpit, `kref stats`, and the periodic no-remote nag.\n\nB provides approve/reject by id; C provides discovery and read surfaces over the\nsame items.\n\n## Test plan (sketch, finalized in the plan)\n\n- Approve draft: retiers to the `q-dest` tier, clears q-labels, resolves the\n  thread, leaves the pending queue; the entry is live and syncable.\n- Approve held op, each op-kind: `set-body` / `add-comment` / `edit-comment` /\n  `resolve` replay faithfully onto the live target; the item is archived\n  `q-status:approved`; the thread is resolved.\n- Stale replay: a held todo `set-body` whose target version advanced refuses with\n  a conflict and does not modify the target.\n- Reject: preserves content to the recovery dir, resolves the thread rejected,\n  archives `q-status:rejected`; the live target is untouched.\n- --force: `new` / `update` / `comment` with `--force` on a flagged body apply in\n  one step and leave a `q-status:approved` audit item; on a clean body they write\n  directly with no item.\n- Carry-overs: a flagged `comment --edit` and `comment --resolve -m` (CLI and MCP)\n  park instead of refuse; approving them replays the edit / the note+resolve.\n- MCP: no force argument exists on any MCP write tool.\n\n## Open questions (resolve in the plan)\n\n- Exact `BaseVersion` capture point: the writer's asserted `if_version` vs the\n  head version read during the write, and the ordering of the secret scan relative\n  to the CAS check at each boundary. Lean: prefer the asserted `if_version` when\n  the surface supplies one, else the head read at scan time.\n- Whether `q-status:approved|rejected` is a label vs a dedicated field. Lean:\n  label, consistent with `q-dest` / `q-review` and cheap for C to filter.\n- Whether approve of a held op archives before or after resolving the thread\n  (both under the lock). Lean: replay -\u003e resolve thread -\u003e archive item, so a\n  mid-sequence failure leaves the item pending and re-runnable.\n"}]}